<subSubSection id="A1D565563F05FF93FF26FEC0FBFBFD2F" lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F05FF93FF26FEC0FD90FEFC" blockId="48.[151,1437,290,424]" lastBlockId="49.[151,1437,150,718]" lastPageId="49" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
Morphology. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F05FF92FEBEFEC0FD72FE81" bold="true" box="[351,658,325,352]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">D VI + I,10–11; A I,10–11;</emphasis>
P 17 (Miller 1986; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F05FF92FC8AFEC0FB68FE80" author="Kovacic, M. &amp; Golani, D." box="[875,1160,326,353]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="417 - 425" refId="ref58262" refString="Kovacic, M. &amp; Golani, D. (2007 b) First record of Papillogobius melanobranchus in the Mediterranean Sea and new data on geographic distributions, bathymetric ranges and morphology of several benthic fishes in the Levant. Cybium, 31 (4), 417 - 425. https: // doi. org / 10.26028 / cybium / 2007 - 314 - 002" type="journal article" year="2007">Kovačić &amp; Golani 2007b</bibRefCitation>
). Moderately small goby with subcylindrical body, laterally compressed towards caudal fin, head slightly depressed and moderately large. Snout large and pointed. Eyes lateral, interorbital moderately wide. Mouth superior, oblique, tip of lower jaw at horizontal level of pupil. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FE53FF10FC96FF51" bold="true" box="[434,886,150,177]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Angle of jaws below rear half of orbit.</emphasis>
Predorsal area and nape scaled. Caudal peduncle slender, lower than body. The first dorsal fin higher than the second dorsal fin, no elongated spines, but 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FAD2FF3CFCDCFF19" bold="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">breeding males with notably enlarged, sail-shaped, first dorsal fin</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F04FF93FCADFF59FC4CFF18" box="[844,940,222,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1863,1887]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,448,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-100@48.[151,1436,448,1839]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 51. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Deltentosteus collonianus. A) photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy. B) Breeding male (the rounded, notably enlarged first dorsal fin, has been injured), photo by S. Le Bris, Saména, Southern France." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601727/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Fig. 51b</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F04FF93FC25FF59FBB6FF18" author="Louisy, P." box="[964,1110,222,249]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refId="ref60639" refString="Louisy, P. (2015) Europe and Mediterranean Marine Fish Identification Guide. 3 rd Edition. Eugen Ulmer Ed., Paris, 512 pp." type="book" year="2015">Louisy 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F04FF93FB82FF59FADBFF18" author="Le Bris, S. &amp; Berenger, L. &amp; Louisy, P." box="[1123,1339,223,249]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refId="ref59988" refString="Le Bris, S., Berenger, L. &amp; Louisy, P. (2017) Signalisation de / Record of Deltentosteus collonianus, 12 March 2017 (obs. 31 January 2017, photo  3514). Fish Watch Forum, Louisy, P. &amp; Francour, P. (Ed.). Available from: https: // www. fish-watch. org (accessed 28 September 2021)" type="url" year="2017">
Le Bris 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FB5EFF59FB11FF18" box="[1215,1265,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F04FF93FAA6FF59FA71FF18" author="Le Bris, S. &amp; Pillon, R. &amp; Louisy, P." box="[1351,1425,223,249]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" refId="ref60064" refString="Le Bris, S., Pillon, R. &amp; Louisy, P. (2019 a) Signalisation de / Record of Deltentosteus collonianus, 02 March 2019 (obs. 27 February 2019, photo  5152). Fish Watch Forum, Louisy, P. &amp; Francour, P. (Ed.). Available from: https: // www. fish-watch. org (accessed 28 September 2021)" type="url" year="2019">2019a</bibRefCitation>
). Caudal fin truncate to slightly emarginate.
</paragraph>
<caption id="BDB066553F05FF92FF76F8C1FF03F847" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601727" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6601727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601727/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" startId="48.[151,250,1863,1887]" targetBox="[151,1436,448,1839]" targetPageId="48">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F05FF92FF76F8C1FF03F847" blockId="48.[151,1437,1863,1958]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F05FF92FF76F8C1FEC4F8BE" bold="true" box="[151,292,1863,1887]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">FIGURE 51.</emphasis>
Live coloration in its natural habitat of 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F05FF92FD34F8C1FC3FF8BE" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1820" box="[725,991,1863,1887]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Deltentosteus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="collonianus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F05FF92FD34F8C1FC3FF8BE" box="[725,991,1863,1887]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Deltentosteus collonianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A) photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy. B) Breeding male (the rounded, notably enlarged first dorsal fin, has been injured), photo by S. Le Bris, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F05FF92FB03F8EDFAD8F863" box="[1250,1336,1899,1922]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Saména,</emphasis>
Southern France.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F04FF93FF26FEA1FBB2FE14" blockId="49.[151,1437,150,718]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Live coloration. Body dorsally mainly brown or beige with 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FC90FEA1FEC4FE84" bold="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">5 pale dorsal saddles, each above a midlateral dark blotch</emphasis>
including one at the caudal-fin base (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F04FF93FD2FFECDFCC2FE84" box="[718,802,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1863,1887]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,448,1839]" captionTargetId="figure-100@48.[151,1436,448,1839]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 51. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Deltentosteus collonianus. A) photo by S. Guerrieri, Tuscany, Italy. B) Breeding male (the rounded, notably enlarged first dorsal fin, has been injured), photo by S. Le Bris, Saména, Southern France." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601727/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FCD6FECDFEA7FE4C" bold="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">The saddles on the back generally conspicuous and usually with black anterior and posterior outlines. The midlateral dark blotches of irregular rhomboid to rounded shape</emphasis>
, anteriorly about 1/3 of body height. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FD0AFE15FE57FE30" bold="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Black mark on caudal-fin base triangular and larger than other midlateral marks.</emphasis>
Ventral half of body whitish. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F04FF93FCEFFE31FA74FE31" bold="true" box="[782,1428,438,465]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">The first dorsal fin without dark markings in females</emphasis>
; one or two black spots on rear margin in males (
